N.Y. / Region

Sylvia Hassenfeld, Philanthropist From Hasbro’s Founding Family, Dies at 93

By PAUL VITELLOAUG. 20, 2014



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Sylvia Hassenfeld, with her great-grandson Kinsey Casdin, announcing a gift to NYU Langone Medical Center in fall 2011.

Credit
            Cindy Ord/Getty Images        



Sylvia Hassenfeld, the matriarch of the founding family of Hasbro, the maker of G.I. Joe, Mr. Potato Head and the Transformers, who became a path-making philanthropist and one of the first women to head a major international Jewish aid organization, died on Saturday at her home in Manhattan. She was 93.Her death was confirmed by her daughter, Ellen Hassenfeld Block.From 1988 to 1992, Mrs. Hassenfeld was the first female president of the American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee, a relief group founded in 1914 to provide social services and refugee assistance for persecuted Jews around the world.During her tenure, she took a hands-on role in negotiating the resettlement of Jews leaving the disintegrating Soviet Union, providing help for Jews remaining in former Soviet bloc states like Romania and Hungary, and arranging the 1991 airlift to Israel of 14,000 Jews from war-torn Ethiopia.She was also the first president of the organization to support the expansion of crisis assistance programs to non-Jews. In 1989, the organization helped to arrange a series of charter flights that ferried some of the most severely injured victims of the 1988 Armenian earthquake to Tel Aviv and Haifa for treatment and rehabilitation. Nonsectarian agricultural aid was also sent to Ethiopia in the late 1980s.Mrs. Hassenfeld was the widow of Merrill L. Hassenfeld, who ran Hasbro — founded in 1923 by Mr. Hassenfeld’s father, Henry, and his uncles Hillel and Herman — in the ’50s and ’60s. Their son Stephen took over the company after Merrill Hassenfeld’s death in 1979. It was the world’s fifth-largest toy company at the time, but had become the largest by the time he died in 1989. Another son, Alan, led Hasbro, which is still under the family’s control, until 2008.While she served for many years as a member of the board and was involved, as the mother of three children, in the early test-marketing of many Hasbro products, Mrs. Hassenfeld was mainly occupied by philanthropic work, her daughter said.
